$\textbf{Project Milestone 2}$

$\textbf{10/14/2022}$

$\textbf{Project Goals:}$

The goal of this project is to explore the temporal and spatial distribution of earthquakes around New Zealand from 1990 - 2022, and investigate the possible relation with the motion of the subducting plates.

The motivation of this project the series of migrating seismic swarms of small magnitude erathquakes which have been happening around New Zealand, with the country recording up to 15000 earthquakes per year.

In this project I will be working alone as required for graduate students and do hope to be working on it whenever time is available as planned.

$\textbf{Project Explanations:}$
This project requires two sets of data, the first one about the earthquakes in the study region and the seond set of data about the motion of the plates on which New Zealand is seated.

The first set of data was obtained from the data management centre called Incorporated Research Institutions for Seismology - IRIS. The data was acquired by downloading it using a code from Observational Python library called ObsPy as shown in the following cells.
The second set of data about the motion of the plates is the Global Positioning System (GPS) data recorded by GPS stations from different parts of the region in New Zealand. This data was obtained from Nevada Geodetic Laboratory website which runs the GPS data for most of the GPS stations around the world.

The fisrt set of data contains four aspects of the earthquake that is the earthquake magnitude, location (latitude and longitude), time and depth at which it occured. The data set comes as a catalog, a default ObsPy format but can be converted into a pandas DataFrame format.
The data catalog is first plotted to take a look at the distribution of earthquakes around the region . It is then read into a DataFrame format and the times column seperated into year and actual time of occurence which enables studying the temporal distribution over years' period.

The second set of data contains the locations and displacements of the the GPS stations with time. This enables calculation of the velocities of the GPS stations which indicate the velocities of the plates with time and can show the changes in the trend for the displacements and velocities which we can study in correspondence with earthquake events occurence.

The mean and median magnitude of the earthquakes, the largest magnitude earthquake ever recorded in the region and the mean, median and largest predicted depths of the earthquakes are shown below. These help characterize the nature of earthquakes recorded in the region, i.e from the mean and median value of the magnitudes, we can infer that the region experinces mainly small magnitude earthquakes. However, majority of the earthquakes are relatively shallow with earthquakes as compared with average depth of the subduction linked earthquakes. This means that these earthquakes are influenced by the upper part of the subducting plates. This means they could have an effect on the plate motion.

The second part of the data from the GPS stations is uploaded and exploered in the following cells.
Ten (10) files each corresponding to a GPS station were downloaded and are read and converted into a DataFrame format. The GPS stations selected started operating in 1995 upto 2002 and their names are output when plots are made. The following stations are picked from the northen island: (AUCK, HIKB, PAEK, NPLY, WGTN) while these are from southern island: (HOKI, LYTT, NLSN, OUSD, VEXA).
This is the part which will clear show whether the plate motion has an influnce and or is being influenced by the earthquakes by looking at the velocities. Since the parameters in this study are less, that is magnitude, depth and velocity, I will not develop a machine leraning model, but rather compare trends of magnitude, depth and velocties. I will also look at more comparative measurement parameters such as heatmap if possible towards the end of this project.

The data is then cleaned and new columns defined for the time duration, displacements and the velocities of the GPS station which represent the motion of the plates.
Xd, Yd and Yd are the displacements in the East-West, North-South and the vertical direction.
Vh, Vz and Vt are the resultant horizontal component, vertical component and the resultant velocities of the GPS stations (plates) evaluated by dividing dispalcements with time durations, and taking appropriate mathematics for composite velocities.

In [203]:
Datafram['YYMMMDD'] = pd.to_datetime(Datafram['YYMMMDD'], format='%y%b%d')
Datafram.rename(columns = {'YYMMMDD':'time','__east(m)':'Xd','_north(m)':'Yd','____up(m)':'Zd'}, inplace=True)
Datafram["year"] = pd.DatetimeIndex(Datafram["time"]).year
Datafram['time_dur'] = Datafram['time'].diff()
Datafram['time_dur'] = Datafram['time_dur'].dt.total_seconds().fillna(1000000)
Datafram["Horiz_disp"] = np.sqrt((Datafram["Xd"])**2 + (Datafram["Yd"])**2)
Datafram["Total_disp"] = np.sqrt((Datafram["Xd"])**2 + (Datafram["Yd"])**2 + (Datafram["Zd"])**2)
Datafram["Vh"] = (1000*Datafram['Horiz_disp'])/Datafram['time_dur']
Datafram["Vz"] = (1000*Datafram['Zd'])/Datafram['time_dur']
Datafram["Vt"] = (1000*Datafram['Total_disp'])/Datafram['time_dur']

Plots for the different components of the velocities are made and anlysed from the below cells.

The horizontal component which is the resultant of the two components of the North-South and East-West velocities is here plotted. From the graphs, we can say that some parts of the plate are accelerating while others are deccerating in the in each of the Island. The graphs also show that some regions have had their velocities altered to the extent that their trend were totally changed. This is shown for example in the WGTN station which changed trend around 2015 which correponds to great rise in the magnitude of earthquakes and lowest in the depths on earthquakes.
